# MonadicSharp — Cursor Rules
# Railway-Oriented Programming for C# · github.com/Danny4897/MonadicSharp
#
# These rules teach Cursor to generate clean, MonadicSharp-first C# code.
# Drop this file in the root of any .NET 8+ project.

## Core philosophy

- Errors are VALUES, not exceptions. Never use try/catch for expected failures.
- Every method that can fail returns `Result<T>`, not void or a nullable.
- Compose operations with `.Bind()` and `.Map()`. Handle at the boundary with `.Match()`.
- No null returns. Use `Option<T>` for "value that may not exist".

---

## ALWAYS do this

### Return Result<T> from any fallible method
```csharp
// GOOD
public Result<User> CreateUser(string name, string email)
    => ValidateName(name)
        .Bind(_ => ValidateEmail(email))
        .Map(_ => new User(name, email));

// BAD — never this
public User CreateUser(string name, string email)
{
    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(name)) throw new ArgumentException("...");
    return new User(name, email);
}
```

### Chain with Bind (fallible) and Map (infallible)
```csharp
// Bind: next step can also fail
Result<Order> order = await ValidateRequest(req)
    .Bind(r => _repo.FindProductAsync(r.ProductId))
    .Bind(product => _repo.CreateOrderAsync(product, req.Quantity))
    .Map(o => o with { CreatedAt = DateTime.UtcNow });

// Map: pure transformation, cannot fail
Result<OrderDto> dto = order.Map(o => new OrderDto(o));
```

### Always unwrap with Match at the boundary
```csharp
// Controller / API endpoint — the ONLY place to unwrap
return result.Match(
    onSuccess: value => Ok(value),
    onFailure: error => error.Type switch
    {
        ErrorType.NotFound   => NotFound(error.Message),
        ErrorType.Validation => BadRequest(new { error.Message, error.Field }),
        ErrorType.Forbidden  => Forbid(),
        ErrorType.Conflict   => Conflict(error.Message),
        _                    => Problem(error.Message)
    }
);
```

### Use semantic Error factories
```csharp
// GOOD — semantic, typed, structured
Error.Validation("Email is invalid", field: "email")
Error.NotFound("User", identifier: userId.ToString())
Error.Forbidden("Requires admin role")
Error.Conflict("Username already taken", resource: "username")
Error.Unexpected("Payment gateway unreachable", exception)

// BAD — never this
throw new ArgumentException("Email is invalid");
throw new KeyNotFoundException("User not found");
return null;
```

### Use Option<T> instead of nulls
```csharp
// GOOD
Option<User> user = _cache.TryGet(id);
string name = user.Map(u => u.Name).GetValueOrDefault("Anonymous");

// BAD
User? user = _cache.TryGet(id);
string name = user?.Name ?? "Anonymous";
```

### Wrap external/legacy code with Result.Try
```csharp
// GOOD — wraps exception-throwing code safely
Result<string> content = Result.Try(() => File.ReadAllText(path));
Result<int>    parsed  = Result.Try(() => int.Parse(input));

// Async version
Result<string> response = await Result.TryAsync(() => httpClient.GetStringAsync(url));
```

### Collect ALL validation errors with Sequence
```csharp
// GOOD — reports all errors at once
var result = new[]
{
    ValidateName(request.Name),
    ValidateEmail(request.Email),
    ValidateAge(request.Age)
}.Sequence();
```

---

## For AI agent / LLM code — use MonadicSharp.AI

Install: `dotnet add package MonadicSharp.AI`

### Use AiError for LLM failures — never catch HttpRequestException
```csharp
// GOOD
if (response.StatusCode == 429)
    return AiError.RateLimit(retryAfter: TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

if (response.StatusCode == 503)
    return AiError.ModelUnavailable(model: "gpt-4o", httpStatusCode: 503);

// BAD
throw new HttpRequestException("Rate limited");
```

### Use WithRetry for resilient LLM calls
```csharp
// Exponential backoff — only retries retriable errors (rate limit, timeout, unavailable)
Result<string> result = await Result.TryAsync(() => llm.CompleteAsync(prompt))
    .WithRetry(maxAttempts: 3, initialDelay: TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
```

### Use AgentResult for multi-step AI pipelines
```csharp
AgentResult<string> result = await AgentResult
    .StartTrace("DocumentProcessor", input)
    .Step("Retrieve", ctx => _db.SearchAsync(ctx))
    .Step("Generate", ctx => _llm.CompleteAsync(ctx))
    .Step("Validate", ctx => ValidateOutput(ctx))
    .ExecuteAsync();
```

### Self-healing JSON output with MonadicSharp.Recovery
```csharp
using MonadicSharp.Recovery;
using MonadicSharp.AI.Extensions;

var result = await _llm.CompleteAsync(prompt)
    .StartFixBranchAsync(
        when:     ErrorPredicates.HasCode(AiError.InvalidOutputCode),
        recovery: (err, attempt) => _llm.RepairJsonAsync(err, attempt),
        maxAttempts: 2);
```

---

## NEVER do these things

```
❌ throw new Exception(...)           → return Error.Create(...)
❌ return null                        → return Option<T>.None or Result.Failure(...)
❌ catch (Exception ex) { ... }       → use Result.Try(() => ...) 
❌ if (result == null) ...            → use .Match() or .Map()
❌ .Value without checking IsSuccess  → always use .Match() or .GetValueOrDefault()
❌ Task<User?> for async fallible ops → Task<Result<User>>
❌ throw in a service/domain method   → return Result<T>.Failure(Error....)
```

---

## Package reference

| Scenario | Package |
|---|---|
| Core ROP (`Result<T>`, `Option<T>`) | `MonadicSharp` |
| LLM/AI errors, retry, agent tracing | `MonadicSharp.AI` |
| Self-healing pipelines (Amber track) | `MonadicSharp.Recovery` |
| Multi-agent orchestration | `MonadicSharp.Agents` |
| Azure services (CosmosDB, Blob, Bus) | `MonadicSharp.Azure` |
| HTTP client with retry | `MonadicSharp.Http` |
| EF Core repository + Unit of Work | `MonadicSharp.Persistence` |
| OpenTelemetry tracing for agents | `MonadicSharp.Telemetry` |
| Everything at once | `MonadicSharp.Framework` |

Full docs: https://github.com/Danny4897/MonadicSharp
